				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\phi$$\end{document}ϕ that correspond to a change in the study conclusions (known as the “tipping point”). A tipping point analysis may be applied to the point estimate or confidence interval (CI) of the exposure effect; for example, to identify the values of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
